The United States, Australia, Brunei Darussalam, India, Indonesia, Japan, Republic of Korea, Malaysia, New Zealand, Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, and Vietnam have come together to establish the Indo-Pacific Economic Framework for Prosperity. The framework aims to promote resilience, sustainability, inclusiveness, economic growth, fairness, and competitiveness in the region. The partners commit to working together to ensure economic recovery and advancement grounded in resilience, sustainability, and inclusivity, particularly in light of the COVID-19 pandemic. They also recognize the importance of strengthening economic competitiveness and cooperation, securing critical supply chains, stimulating job growth, and improving economic opportunities for vulnerable groups. The partners plan to focus on pillars such as trade, supply chains, clean energy and decarbonization, infrastructure, and tax and anti-corruption measures. They invite other Indo-Pacific partners to join their efforts and are committed to collaborating in a flexible manner that delivers tangible benefits for their peoples. The ultimate goal is to enhance regional economic connectivity and integration, boost commerce, trade, and investments, and improve standards and access to opportunities for workers, companies, and people in their combined markets.